+| Weakness | CWE-705 (Incorrect Control Flow Scoping) |
+| Affected API | `once(emitter, name, { signal })` — optional `AbortSignal` |
+
+---
+
+## Vulnerability Description
+
+In versions that support an optional `AbortSignal`, when the signal is aborted the promise returned by `once()` can remain in a **permanently pending state**. Event listeners are removed, but the promise is never resolved or rejected, causing any `await` or `.then()` usage to hang indefinitely.
+
+The vulnerable pattern (present from 2.0.0 through 3.0.0):
+
+```ts
+signal?.addEventListener('abort', cleanup);
+// cleanup() removes listeners but does not call resolve() or reject()
+```
+
+Additionally, if `signal.aborted === true` at call time, affected versions do not reject immediately.
+
+**Key point for 1.1.2:** This description applies only to releases that **accept an `AbortSignal` option**. **@tootallnate/once@1.1.2 does not.**
+
+---
+
+## Affected vs Not Affected Versions
+
+Per [OSV CVE-2026-3449](https://osv.dev/vulnerability/CVE-2026-3449) and [GHSA-vpq2-c234-7xj6](https://github.com/advisories/GHSA-vpq2-c234-7xj6):
+
+| Status | Versions |
+|--------|----------|
+| **Affected (AbortSignal API present, unfixed)** | 2.0.0 – 3.0.0 |
+| **Fixed upstream** | 3.0.1+ |
+| **Not affected (no AbortSignal API)** | 1.x (including **1.1.2**) |
+
+OSV lists all versions before 3.0.1 in a coarse version range. Scanners may flag **1.1.2** without verifying that the **`AbortSignal` option exists** in that release.
+
+---
+
+## Why once@1.1.2 Is Not Affected
+
+**CVE-2026-3449 does not apply to @tootallnate/once@1.1.2** because the **sole attack surface — the optional `AbortSignal` parameter — was not introduced until 2.0.0**.
+
+Verified facts (direct inspection of upstream tag `1.1.2`):
+
+- `src/index.ts` exports `once(emitter, name)` with **no third-argument options object**
+- Cancellation uses a **`cancel()` method** on `CancelablePromise`, not `AbortSignal`
+- There is **no** `addEventListener('abort', ...)` call anywhere in the 1.1.2 source tree
+- There is **no** `src/types.ts` with an `AbortSignal` interface
+
+The 1.1.2 API:
+
+```ts
+function once<T>(emitter: EventEmitter, name: string): once.CancelablePromise<T>
+```
+
+Because callers cannot pass `{ signal }` to `once()` on 1.1.2, the promise-hang code path described by CVE-2026-3449 **cannot be reached**.
+
+---
+
+## API Comparison: 1.1.2 vs 2.0.0
+
+| Feature | once@1.1.2 | once@2.0.0+ |
+|---------|------------|-------------|
+| Cancellation mechanism | `.cancel()` on promise | Optional `{ signal: AbortSignal }` |
+| Third argument | None | `{ signal?: AbortSignal }` |
+| Abort listener | Not present | `signal?.addEventListener('abort', ...)` |
+| CVE-2026-3449 exposure | **None** | Present until 3.0.1 |
+
+The functional CVE fix (proper `onAbort` handler, `signal.aborted` check, `AbortError` reject) belongs in hooks for **2.0.0+**, not 1.1.2.
+
+---
+
+## Verification
+
+Upstream source at tag `1.1.2` (`3948afc`):
+
+```bash
+git clone --depth 1 --branch 1.1.2 https://github.com/TooTallNate/once.git
+grep -r 'AbortSignal\|signal' src/   # no matches
+grep -r 'addEventListener' src/      # no matches
+```
+
+Attempting to apply a functional CVE-2026-3449 patch (as used for 2.0.0) to 1.1.2 source **fails** — the hunk expects `cleanup`, `onAbort`, and `reject` structures that do not exist in 1.1.2's `src/index.ts`.
+
+---
+
+## Why You Must NOT Patch once@1.1.2 Manually
+
+Attempting to backport AbortSignal-handling fixes onto once@1.1.2 is **incorrect**:
+
+- The vulnerable API (`{ signal }`) **does not exist** in 1.1.2
+- Functional patches target `src/types.ts` and abort-listener logic **absent from this version**
+- A comment-only or partial patch **does not remediate** anything and may break the build
+- Adding AbortSignal support would be a **feature addition**, not a security backport, and would change the public API
+
+**Conclusion:** There is nothing to patch for CVE-2026-3449 on @tootallnate/once@1.1.2.
+
